The JSE’s all share index looked set for a second day of losses on Wednesday, judging from Asian markets trading ahead of its opening. The all share index closed 1.1% lower at 58,977 points on Tuesday, a 3.8% decline from the 61,299 record set on November 21. Tokyo’s Nikkei 225 index was down 1.6%, Hong Kong’s Hang Seng index was down 1.25% and Sydney’s S&P/ASX 200 index was down 0.53% ahead of the JSE’s opening on Wednesday. Asian markets took their cue from Wall Street, were all three major indices continued a three-day slide on Tuesday.  The S&P 500 index fell 0.4%. The rand strengthening 1.6% against the dollar amplified this into a 0.9% drop to R36.05 for its JSE-listed exchange-traded fund, CoreShares S&P 500. The rand was at R13.48/$, R15.96/€ and R18.10/£ at 6.40am. Frankfurt-and Johannesburg-listed Steinhoff International’s share price has fallen 18.2% since Monday, when it said it would release its results for the year to end-September on Wednesday as scheduled, but they would not be signed by its auditors. "The supervisory board and the statutory auditors of the company have not yet finalised their review of certain matters and circumstances, most of which were raised by the criminal and tax investigation in Germany," Steinhoff said.